r labelled Reason (R). Select the correct answer from the codes (A), (B), (C) and (D) as given below. Both Assertion (A) and Reason (R) are true and Reason (R) is the correct explanation of the Assertion (A). Both Assertion (A) and Reason (R) are true, but Reason (R) is not the correct explanation of the Assertion (A). Assertion (A) is true, but Reason (R) is false. Assertion (A) is false, but Reason (R) is true. 19. Assertion (A): The shaded portion of the graph represents the feasible region for the given Linear Programming Problem (LPP). {tex}\operatorname{Min} Z=50 x+70 y{/tex} {tex}	ext { subject to constraints }{/tex} {tex}2 x+y \geq 8, x+2 y \geq 10, x, y \geq 0{/tex} {tex}Z=50 x+70 y 	ext { has a minimum value}{/tex} {tex}=380 	ext { at } B(2,4){/tex} Reason (R): The region representing 50x {tex}+70 {y} \lt 380{/tex} does not have any point common with the feasible region. a. Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A. b. Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A. c. A is true but R is false. d. A is false but R is true. 1 20. Assertion (A): Let {tex}{A}=\{{x} \in {R}:-1 \leq {x} \leq 1\}{/tex} . If {tex}{f}: {A} ightarrow {A}{/tex} be defined as {tex}f(x)=x^{2}{/tex} , then {tex}f{/tex} is not an onto function. Reason {tex}(R):{/tex} If {tex}{y}=-1 \in {~A}{/tex} , then {tex}{x}= \pm \sqrt{-1} 
otin {~A}{/tex} . a. Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A. b. Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A. c. A is true but R is false. d. A is false but R is true. 1 SECTION-B This section comprises 5 Very Short Answer (VSA) type questions of 2 marks each. 21. Find the domain of {tex}\sin ^{-1}\left(x^{2}-3ight){/tex} . 2 22. Let the volume of a metallic hollow sphere be constant. If the inner radius increases at the rate of {tex}2 {~cm} / {s}{/tex} , find the rate of increase of the outer radius when the radii are 2 cm and 4 cm respectively. 2 23. A man needs to hang two lanterns on a straight wire whose end points have coordinates {tex}{A}(4,1,-2){/tex} and {tex}{B}(6,2,-3){/tex} . Find the coordinates of the points where he hangs the lanterns such that these points trisect the wire AB. 2 24. (i) Differentiate {tex} rac{\sin {x}}{\sqrt{\cos {x}}}{/tex} with respect to x. 2 OR (ii) If {tex}{y}=5 \cos {x}-3 \sin {x}{/tex} , prove that {tex} rac{{d}^{2} {y}}{{dx}^{2}}+{y}=0{/tex} . 2 25. (i) Find a vector of magnitude 5 which is perpendicular to both the vectors {tex}3 \hat{i}-2 \hat{j}+\hat{k}{/tex} and {tex}4 \hat{i}+3 \hat{j}-2 \hat{k}{/tex} . 2 OR (ii) Let {tex}\vec{a}, \vec{b}{/tex} and {tex}\vec{c}{/tex} be three vectors such that {tex}\vec{a} \cdot \vec{b}=\vec{a} \cdot \vec{c}{/tex} and {tex}\vec{a} 	imes \vec{b}=\vec{a} 	imes \vec{c}, \vec{a} 
